<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1364,2075]" box="[136,1050,1364,1391]" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis box="[136,256,1364,1390]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">Etymology</emphasis>
.— 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lat.)" baseAuthorityName="Lat." box="[298,448,1364,1390]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pallens">
<emphasis box="[298,379,1364,1390]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">pallens</emphasis>
(Lat.)
</taxonomicName>
refers to the pale color of the basidiomes when fresh.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1364,2075]" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">
Basidiomes resupinate, adnate, cream when fresh becoming straw colored to pale brown upon drying, usually growing on branches and forming patches with up to 8 × 
<quantity box="[772,851,1436,1463]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" unit="cm" value="3.5">3.5 cm</quantity>
. Margins very thin to absent, entire, up to 
<quantity box="[1319,1384,1436,1463]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
wide. Hymenophore hydnoid, teeth often laterally flattened, 2–4 per mm, solitary or fused at the bases, with acute apices, generally 2–4(–5) mm long. Context very thin, homogeneous, white to cream, somewhat fibrous, up to 
<quantity box="[1295,1381,1508,1535]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
thick.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1364,2075]" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">
Hyphal system monomitic. Generative hyphae clamped, thin to slightly thick walled, CB+; tramal hyphae 2.5–5 µm wide, straight to dichotomously branched, subicular hyphae similar, but more often branched and tortuous. Cystidia of 
<specimenCount box="[166,274,1617,1643]" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
present. Tramal cystidia numerous, thin-walled, hyaline, smooth, fusiform, clavate or oboclavate, obtuse at the apex, embedded in the trama or protruding in the hymenium, strongly colored in cotton blue, 6–10 µm wide, widened part up to 35 µm long, CB+. Hymenial cystidia similar to tramal cystidia in shape, but usually slightly smaller and arising from the subhymenium and hymenium, 4–9 µm wide and up to 20 µm long. Basidia clavate, tetrasporate, 12–18 × 4–6 μm. Basidiospores hyaline, smooth, broadly ellipsoid, CB+, IKI-, (4.5–)4.8–6.1(–6.4) × (3.2–)3.4–4.1(– 4.3) μm, Lm × Wm = 5.4 × 3.7 μm, Q = 1.4–1.6, Qm = 1.5 (n = 110/4).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1364,2075]" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis box="[189,510,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">Ecology and Distribution.—</emphasis>
Found growing on dead wood of unidentified angiosperms. Known from southern and southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[330,402,1868,1894]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,1364,2075]" lastBlockId="5.[136,1451,158,256]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="164" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis box="[189,686,1904,1930]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">
Comments.— 
<taxonomicName box="[339,686,1904,1930]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pallens">Pseudolagarobasidium pallens</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is characterized by the subceraceous, cream to pale buff basidiomes with hydnoid hymenophore, usually presenting laterally flattened teeth fused at the bases. Macroscopically, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nakasone &amp; D. L. Lindner" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="Berk. &amp; Broome" box="[1338,1451,1941,1966]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pronum">
<emphasis box="[1338,1451,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">P. pronum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nakasone" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Pouzar" box="[187,352,1977,2002]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="conspicuum">
<emphasis box="[187,352,1977,2002]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">P. conspicuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar due to the pale colored basidiomes, but they differ by the more chalky and brittle consistency. In addition, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nakasone &amp; D. L. Lindner" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="Berk. &amp; Broome" box="[424,541,2013,2038]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pronum">
<emphasis box="[424,541,2013,2038]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">P. pronum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has and smaller basidiospores, 4.0–5.5 × 3–3.7(−4.3) μm, and it is distributed in Asia and 
<collectingCountry box="[279,385,2048,2074]" name="Australia" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">Australia</collectingCountry>
, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nakasone" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Pouzar" box="[472,638,2049,2074]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="conspicuum">
<emphasis box="[472,638,2049,2074]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="163">P. conspicuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in the European continent. (
<bibRefCitation author="Nakasone, K. K. &amp; Lindner, D. L." box="[1133,1447,2048,2074]" pageId="4" pageNumber="163" pagination="155 - 169" refId="ref6374" refString="Nakasone, K. K. &amp; Lindner, D. L. (2012) Taxonomy of Pseudolagarobasidium (Polyporales, Basidiomycota). Fungal Diversity 55 (1): 155 - 169. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 13225 - 012 - 0161 - 1" type="journal article" year="2012">Nakasone &amp; Lindner 2012</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nakasone, K. K." box="[136,315,158,185]" pageId="5" pageNumber="164" pagination="369 - 397" refId="ref6427" refString="Nakasone, K. K. (2015) Taxonomic studies in Chrysoderma, Corneromyces, Dendrophysellum, Hyphoradulum, and Mycobonia. Mycotaxon 130: 369 - 397. https: // doi. org / 10.5248 / 130.369" type="journal article" year="2015">Nakasone 2015</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nakasone &amp; D. L. Lindner" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="Hjortstam &amp; Ryvarden" box="[335,707,158,184]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="164" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="venustum">
<emphasis box="[335,707,158,184]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="164">Pseudolagarobasidium venustum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was also described from 
<collectingCountry box="[997,1068,158,184]" name="Brazil" pageId="5" pageNumber="164">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, but is easily distinguished by the pale yellow to orange basidiomes, teeth studded with knobs or warts and smaller basidiospores 4–5 × 3.2–3.7 µm (
<bibRefCitation author="Nakasone, K. K. &amp; Lindner, D. L." box="[143,448,230,256]" pageId="5" pageNumber="164" pagination="155 - 169" refId="ref6374" refString="Nakasone, K. K. &amp; Lindner, D. L. (2012) Taxonomy of Pseudolagarobasidium (Polyporales, Basidiomycota). Fungal Diversity 55 (1): 155 - 169. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 13225 - 012 - 0161 - 1" type="journal article" year="2012">Nakasone &amp; Lindner 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
