<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1451,1961,2060]" pageId="5" pageNumber="164">
Phylogenetically, 
<taxonomicName box="[392,502,1961,1987]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="164" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pallens">
<emphasis box="[392,502,1961,1987]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="164">P. pallens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms a sister clade with 
<taxonomicName box="[801,934,1961,1987]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="164" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="belizense">
<emphasis box="[801,934,1961,1987]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="164">P. belizense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[951,1018,1961,1987]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[136,229,1824,1846]" captionTargetBox="[193,1419,562,1754]" captionTargetId="figure-138@3.[151,1436,511,1800]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Phylogenetic relationships in Cerrenaceae clade inferred from a combined dataset of ITS and nLSU sequences, conducted by Bayesian inference.All sequences generated in this study are indicated in bold faces. Numbers at branches indicate Bayesian posterior probability values / bootstrap frequency. Two letter codes after voucher specimens denote country of origin (ISO 3166 - Alpha 2). The bar indicates the number of expected substitutions per position." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876000" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876000/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="164">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName box="[1162,1294,1961,1987]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Phanerochaetaceae" genus="Pseudolagarobasidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Polyporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="164" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="belizense">
<emphasis box="[1162,1294,1961,1987]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="164">P. belizense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished morphologically by the odontioid to warty grayish basidiomes (
<figureCitation box="[996,1063,1997,2023]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1194,1216]" captionTargetBox="[151,1376,281,1169]" captionTargetId="figure-58@5.[151,1436,281,1169]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dried basidiomes. A – B. Pseudolagarobasidium belizense (DLC 04–31, holotype); C. P. pallens (534/17 holotype). Scale bars:A = 1 cm, B–C = 5 mm Photos: Mariana Drewinski (A and B) and Mauro Westphalen (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876002" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876002/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="164">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), more densely arranged hyphae in the trama of the teeth and subiculum, and slightly smaller basidiospores 4.2–5.0(–5.2) × 3–3.5(–3.7) µm (
<figureCitation box="[1319,1387,2033,2059]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1820,1842]" captionTargetBox="[185,1412,1290,1773]" captionTargetId="figure-99@5.[151,1436,1277,1796]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pseudolagarobasidium pallens (A–B) and P. belizense (C). A. Section of the basidiome showing the hymenium and trama. B. Basidiospores. C. Basidiospores (from holotype). Scale bars: A = 10 µm, B–C = 5 µm. Drawings by Viviana Motato-Vásquez." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876004/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="164">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
